{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"alias":"houndish-sapient-fantail","creation_channel":"python","description":"# Add focused prerequisite consistency review\n\n## Goal\nEvaluate whether a ticket's plan remains consistent with each direct prerequisite without injecting prerequisite material into every general reviewer or changing existing parent/child review behavior.\n\n## Implementation\n- Register a specialized criterion that triggers deterministically only when direct prerequisites exist.\n- Supply the whole subject plan plus each prerequisite's current narrow material. Reuse the canonical prerequisite resolution developed for plan-material pins.\n- Batch multiple independent subject-to-prerequisite evaluations when whole prerequisite blocks fit within the existing context headroom. Never split the subject or a prerequisite.\n- Require one explicit disposition per prerequisite canonical ID. Each blocking finding must identify exactly one canonical prerequisite ID; unattributed or invalidly attributed findings are indeterminate and cannot block.\n- Keep batching semantically neutral: do not create cross-prerequisite findings whose availability depends on bin membership.\n- Give Pass 2 the same subject/prerequisite map so it verifies both consistency and attribution. Route upheld findings through normal Pass 3 and the execution-phase floor.\n- On a context-limit error retry with smaller bins. When subject plus one prerequisite cannot fit at the largest supported window, produce the existing too-large remediation.\n- Extend the existing child-packing fidelity approach with a one-prerequisite-per-call baseline measuring recall, false acceptance, required coverage, and attribution, including tail items.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] Only the focused criterion receives prerequisite material; general criteria and all existing parent/child handling remain unchanged.\n- [ ] Token-budget batching preserves whole inputs, produces a disposition for every prerequisite, and cannot block on missing or incorrect canonical-ID attribution.\n- [ ] Pass-2 verification, smaller-bin fallback, oversized remediation, and fidelity comparison against one-per-call are covered by deterministic tests plus the established opt-in live evaluation path.\n\n## Verification\n- Run focused registry, Pass-1/Pass-2, sizing, and fidelity spot-eval tests.\n- Run the existing opt-in prerequisite fidelity evaluation and record its result on the ticket.\n- Run make check and the non-integration test suite.\n","id":"7c27-10fc-4fe6-4b56","parent_id":"jira-reb-1160","priority":2,"tags":["plan-review","jira-reb-1160"],"ticket_type":"story","title":"Review direct prerequisites with a focused token-budget-batched criterion"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1784517374432472001,"uuid":"60edae65-0eeb-4fa6-88dc-b69b0996e314"}